Now I have all the information. Let me also quickly verify the DumpASTToScreen guard condition more precisely — the attack report at D-07 claims it uses `dumpToScreen` without the MANGLING guard, but I saw the actual code has the guard.

<!-- chunk-boundary -->



The guard `i < static_cast<int>(CompileStage::MANGLING)` means DumpASTToScreen only runs if compilation stopped before MANGLING. Since RELEASE_AST would be after CHIR (which is after MANGLING), `i` would be well past MANGLING, so this guard protects against D-07. The attack report's D-07 misrepresents the actual code — it shows `dumpToScreen` without the MANGLING guard.

Now let me check one more thing — whether DiagAdapter is a stack-local object in AST2CHIR or has a longer lifetime.

<!-- chunk-boundary -->



DiagAdapter is passed by pointer/reference to CHIR optimization passes and checkers. Let me check where it's created and its lifetime.

<!-- chunk-boundary -->



Critical finding: `DiagAdapter` is a member of `CHIR::Package` (line 214 in CHIR.h), not a stack-local object. This means it lives as long as the CHIR package, which persists through CodeGen. The `posRange2MacroCallMap` holding AST pointers is indeed a real concern — D-06 is confirmed.

